# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: chris-bambery
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Written from a far left perspective, the book briefly covers Scottish ancient history, before documenting events from the Middle Ages until 2014, focussing on the struggle of workers and Scottish perspectives on the UK's political parties and sense of national identity.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It was written by Trotskyist Chris Bambery.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book has fifteen chapters before its conclusion.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It briefly mentions ancient history before delving into the Middle Ages, documenting the historical urbanisation of Scotland and the role of Scots in British colonisation campaigns.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It notes the pattern of a few Scottish urbanites profiting from colonial conquests and sending their earnings to England, rather than benefiting the Scottish people.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] It notes the rising worker solidarity, from 1880s onwards, comparing the most robust rise of class consciousness with Wales, both more widespread than in England.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book notes the Labour Party leader Ramsay MacDonald's support for austerity measures, costing the party support in Scotland in the 1930s.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Bambery writes about the influence of folk music on the Scottish sense of national identity and as a tool to advance pacifism.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] He also notes the Scottish discomfort with the Communist Party of Britain and the influence of Thatcherite politics, prompting the 1997 Scottish devolution referendum, devolution, and the creation of the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book notes Scottish "disgust" for the Iraq War amidst wider protests against Tony Blair's "neoliberalism".
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Bambery describes Scottish National Party opportunism as deceptive, painting the party's politicians as being closer to neoliberalism than they claim.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] He describes Scottish independence voters as seekers of democracy.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] The book's conclusion covers the increasing wealth gap in Scotland.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Paul Buhle, writing in *Monthly Review*, described the book as "splendid".
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] Seán Damer, of Edinburgh University's School of Social and Political Science, described it as "well-written, well-documented, readable and provocative", crediting the author for telling history from the perspective of working-class Scots.
[src:chris-bambery/a-people-s-history-of-scotland] He describes the book as being written from a Marxist perspective.*The Herald* gave the book a mixed review describing it as good and readable, but also characterising it as campaigning ahead of the 2014 independence referendum scheduled a few months after the book's publication.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Founded in 1872 as **University College Wales, Aberystwyth**, it became a founder member of the University of Wales in 1894, and changed its name to the **University College of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In the mid-1990s, the university again changed its name to become the **University of Wales, Aberystwyth**.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] On 1 September 2007, the University of Wales ceased to be a federal university and Aberystwyth University became independent again.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The annual income of the institution for 2024–2025 was £124.8 million of which £19.2 million was from research grants and contracts, with an expenditure of £130.3 million.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In the middle of the 19th century, eminent Welsh people were advocating the establishment of a university in the principality of Wales.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] One of these, Thomas Nicholas, whose book, *Middle and High Class Schools, and University Education for Wales* (1863), is said to have "exerted great influence on educated Welshmen".
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Funded through public and private subscriptions, and with five regional committees (London, Manchester, Liverpool, North and South Wales) guaranteeing funds for the first three years' running costs, the university opened in October 1872 with 26 students.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Thomas Charles Edwards was the principal.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In October 1875, chapels in Wales raised the next tranche of funds from over 70,000 contributors.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Until 1893, when the college joined the University of Wales as a founder member, students applying to Aberystwyth sat the University of London's entrance exams.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 1885, a fire damaged what is now known as the Old College, Aberystwyth, and in 1897 the first 14 acres of what became the main Penglais campus were purchased.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Incorporated by royal charter in 1893, the university installed Albert Edward, Prince of Wales, as chancellor in 1896, the same year it awarded an honorary degree to the former British prime minister, William Gladstone.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The university's coat of arms dates from the 1880s.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The shield features two red dragons to symbolise Wales, and an open book to symbolise learning.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The crest, an eagle or phoenix above a flaming tower, may signify the college's rebirth after the 1885 fire.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The motto is *Nid Byd, Byd Heb Wybodaeth* ('a world without knowledge is no world at all').
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In the early 1900s, the university added courses that included law, applied mathematics, pure mathematics and botany.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Department for International Politics, which Aberystwyth says is the oldest such department in the world, was founded in 1919.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] By 1977, the university's staff included eight Fellows of the Royal Society, such as Gwendolen Rees, the first Welsh woman to be elected an FRS.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Sports and Exercise Science was established in 2000.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Joint honours psychology degrees were introduced in September 2007, and single honours psychology in 2009.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The chancellor of the university is Dame Nicola Davies, who took up the position in January 2025.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The visitor of the university is an appointment made by the privy council, under the royal charter of the university.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Since July 2014, the holder of this office is Sir Roderick Evans.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2011, the university appointed a new vice chancellor under whom the academic departments were restructured as larger subject-themed institutes.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2022, the university celebrated its 150th anniversary, being established in 1872 (known at the time as The University College of Wales).
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Sciences (IBERS) is a research and teaching centre which brings together staff from the Institutes of Rural Sciences and Biological Sciences and the Institute of Grassland and Environmental Research (IGER).
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Around 360 research, teaching and support staff conduct basic, strategic and applied research in biology.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The institute is located in two areas; one at the main teaching Penglais campus and another rural research hub at the Gogerddan campus.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 1998, the Department of Economics (founded in 1912), the Department of Accounting and Finance (founded in 1979) and the Centre for Business Studies merged to create the School of Management and Business.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the School joined the Department of Information Studies and the Department of Law and Criminology at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The school was shortlisted for "Business School of the Year" in the *Times Higher Education* Awards (2014).
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2016, the institute, minus the Department of Information Studies, was renamed the Institute of Business and Law, the remaining departments being renamed Aberystwyth Business School and Aberystwyth Law School.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Computer Science (founded in 1970), conducts research in automated reasoning, computational biology, vision graphics and visualisation and intelligent robotics.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] AberMUD, the first popular internet-based MUD, was written in the department by then-student Alan Cox.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Jan Pinkava, another graduate, won an Oscar for his short animated film *Geri's Game*.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Geography and Earth Sciences (IGES) was formed, in 1989, from the former Departments of Geography (established in 1918) and Geology.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Bowen map library, containing 80,000 maps and 500 atlases.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The College of Librarianship Wales (CLW) was established at Llanbadarn Fawr in 1964, in response to a recommendation for the training of bilingual librarians that was made in the Bourdillon Report on *Standards of public library service in England* (HMSO, 1962).
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The college grew rapidly, developing close links to the Welsh speaking and professional communities, acquiring an international reputation and pioneering flexible and distance learning courses.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] It claimed to be Europe's largest institution for training librarians.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The independent college merged with the university in August 1989 and the department moved to the Penglais campus a quarter of a century later.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Following the merger, the new department took over responsibility for existing offerings in archives administration and modern records management.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Department of International Politics is the oldest of its kind in the world.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] It was founded, shortly after the First World War in 1919, with the stated purpose of furthering political understanding of the world in the hope of avoiding such conflicts in the future.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] This goal led to the creation of the Woodrow Wilson Chair of International Politics, with Wilson having played a significant role in its creation.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 700 students from 40 countries studying at undergraduate, masters and PhD levels.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] It achieved a 95% score for student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey, placing it as the highest-ranking politics department in Wales and within the UK's top ten.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The department has hosted notable academic staff in the field including E.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Carr, Leopold Kohr, Andrew Linklater, Ken Booth, Steve Smith, Michael Cox, Michael MccGwire, Jenny Edkins and Colin J.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Law and Criminology (founded in 1901) is housed in the Hugh Owen Building on the Penglais campus, and includes the *Centre for Welsh Legal Affairs*, a specialist research centre.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] All academic staff are engaged in research, and the *International Journal of Biosciences and the Law* and the *Cambrian Law Review* are edited in the department.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the department joined the Department of Information Studies and the School of Management and Business at a new campus at Llanbadarn Fawr, as part of a newly created Institute of Management, Law and Information Studies.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In September 2018, the department moved back to the Hugh Owen Building, based in the Penglais campus, and its name changed from Aberystwyth Law School to the Department of Law and Criminology.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth has taught modern languages since 1874.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] French, German, Italian and Spanish courses are taught at both beginners' and advanced levels, in a research-active academic environment.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] One of its research projects is the *Anglo-Norman Dictionary*, based in Aberystwyth since 2001 and available online since 2005.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Physics was first taught at Aberystwyth as part of Natural Philosophy, Astronomy and Mathematics under N.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Grimley, soon after the foundation of the University College.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] It became a department in 1877, under the leadership of F.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The department was located in the south wing of what is now the Old College, but later moved to the Physics Building on the Penglais Campus.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The first chair in Physics was offered to D.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Before the First World War, much of the early research in the department was undertaken in Germany.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Early research in the 1900s was concerned with electrical conductivity and quantum theory, later moving into thermal conductivity and acoustics.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 1931, the department hosted the Faraday Centenary Exhibition.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Williams was appointed to the Chair of Physics in 1938 where he continued his research into sub-atomic particles using a cloud chamber.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Following the Second World War, research was concerned with mechanical and nuclear physics, later moving into the fields of air density, experimental rocket launching equipment and radar.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, Aberystwyth established psychology as a "Centre for Applied Psychology" within the Department of International Politics.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] By 2011, psychology had moved into its current premises in Penbryn 5 on the Penglais Campus.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The department has over 550 undergraduate students, with degrees accredited by the British Psychological Society and is home to an MSc in Behaviour Change.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The main campus of the university is situated on Penglais Hill, overlooking the town of Aberystwyth and Cardigan Bay, and comprises most of the university buildings, Arts Centre, Students' Union, and many of the student residences.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Just below Penglais Campus is the National Library of Wales, one of Britain's five legal deposit libraries.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The landscaping of the Penglais Campus is historically significant and is listed at Grade II* on the Cadw/ICOMOS Register of Parks and Gardens of Special Historic Interest in Wales.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Llanbadarn Centre is located approximately one mile to the east of the Penglais Campus, near Llanbadarn Fawr, overlooking the town and Cardigan Bay to the west, with the backdrop of the Cambrian Mountains to the east.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Llanbadarn Centre hosted Aberystwyth Law School and Aberystwyth Business School, which together formed the Institute of Business and Law.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Department of Information Studies is also based there.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Additionally, the Llanbadarn Campus is the site of the Aberystwyth branch of Coleg Ceredigion (a further education college, and not part of the university).
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] At Gogerddan, on the outskirts of town is located the university's major centre for research in land based sciences and the main centre for the Institute of Biological, Environmental and Rural Science.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The School of Art is located between the Penglais Campus and the centre of Aberystwyth, in what was originally the Edward Davies Memorial Chemistry Laboratories.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] A listed building, the Edward Davies Building is one of the finest examples of architecture in Aberystwyth.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The site of the original university is the Old College, currently the subject of the "New Life for Old College" project which aims to transform it into an integrated centre of heritage, culture, learning and knowledge exchange.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The university opened an international campus in Mauritius in 2015 operating as *Aberystwyth University (Mauritian Branch Campus)* and registered with the Tertiary Education Commission of Mauritius, but closed it to new enrolments two years later due to low enrolment numbers.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Less than 200 students enrolled with the Mauritius campus, which had the capacity for 2,000 students, before its 2018 closure and the university lost more than a million pounds as a result of the venture.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Most of the student residences are on campus, with the rest in walking distance of the campus and Aberystwyth town centre.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Accommodation ranges from "traditional" catered residences to en-suite self-catered accommodation, and from budget rooms to more luxurious studio apartments.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] All have wired access to the university's computer network and a support network of residential tutors.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Disabled access rooms are available within the existing student village.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University is placed in the UK's top 40 universities in the main national rankings.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] It is ranked 38th for 132 UK university rankings in *The Times/Sunday Times Good University Guide* for 2023, and the first university to be given the prestigious award "University of the year for teaching quality" for two consecutive years, in 2018 and 2019.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The *Times Higher Education World University Rankings* placed it in the 301—350 group for 800 university rankings, compared with 351—400 the previous year, and the *QS World University Rankings* placed it at the 432nd position for 2019, compared with 481—490 of the previous year.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2015, UK employers from "predominantly business, IT and engineering sectors" listed Aberystwyth equal 49th in their 62-place employability rankings for UK graduates, according to a *Times Higher Education* report.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was rated in the top ten of UK higher education institutions for overall student satisfaction in the 2016 National Student Survey (NSS).
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University was shortlisted in four categories in the *Times Higher Education* Leadership and Management Awards (THELMAs) (2015).
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Aberystwyth University has been awarded the Silver Award under the Corporate Health Standard (CHS), the quality mark for workplace health promotion run by Welsh Government.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The university has been awarded an Athena SWAN Charter Award, recognising commitment to advancing women's careers in science, technology, engineering, maths and medicine (STEMM) in higher education and research.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2007, the university came under criticism for its record on sustainability, ranking 97th out of 106 UK higher education institutions in that year's Green League table.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2012 the university was listed in the table's "Failed, no award" section, ranking equal 132nd out of 145.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2013 it ranked equal 135th out of 143, and was listed again as "Failed, no award".
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Following the university's initiatives to address sustainability, it received an EcoCampus Silver Phase award in October 2014.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In October 2015, the university's Penglais Campus became the first university campus in Wales to achieve the Green Flag Award.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The Green Flag Award is a UK-wide partnership, delivered in Wales by Keep Wales Tidy with support from Natural Resources Wales, and is the mark of a high quality park or green space.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In 2013, the University and College Union alleged bullying behaviour by Aberystwyth University managers, and said staff were fearful for their jobs.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The singer Peter Karrie resigned his honorary fellowship in protest, he said, at the apparent determination to "ruin one of the finest arts centres in the country", and because he was "unable to support any regime that can treat their staff in such a cruel and appalling manner".
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] In Autumn 2024, students protested the reduction of opening hours at Hugh Owen Library, a cost-cutting measure.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] Students argued that the university had continued to promote their 24/7 Library until recent open days, and that they were going back on promises which had attracted many students to the University.
[src:chris-bambery/aberystwyth-university] The University initially met with students to discuss options to restore the library's original opening hours, but later rejected further requests for meetings, and refused to negotiate any further.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He became involved in revolutionary politics as a student at Balliol College, Oxford, where he studied for a BA and came to know Christopher Hitchens, then himself active in the International Socialists (the SWP's forerunner).
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] The earliest writing by Callinicos for the International Socialists was an analysis of the student movement of the period.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] His other early writings focused on southern Africa and the French structuralist-Marxist philosopher Louis Althusser.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] In 1977, Callinicos married Joanna Seddon, a fellow Oxford doctoral student.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] Callinicos participated in the Counter-Summit to the IMF/World Bank Meeting in Prague, September 2000 and the demonstration against the G8 in Genoa, June 2001.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He has also been involved in organising the Social Forum movement in Europe.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He was a contributor to *Dictionnaire Marx Contemporain* (2001), and has written articles in *New Left Review*.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He was Professor of Politics at the University of York before being appointed Professor of European Studies at King's College London in September 2005.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He succeeded Chris Harman as editor of *International Socialism* in January 2010 shortly after Harman died and is a British correspondent for *Actuel Marx*.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] Callinicos joined the central committee of the SWP in the late 1970s; he retained this position until December 2025.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] Callinicos was a critic of the humanitarian interventions in Bosnia and Kosovo, arguing that they were conducted solely to promote the global capitalist expansion.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He has described Russia's invasion of Ukraine as "an ongoing battle between imperialist rivals, driving forward by capitalist competition".
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He has argued against Western efforts to provide arms for Ukraine.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] Callinicos disagreed with those who argued for the need to change the existing system.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] Callinicos took a prominent position on another issue which had divided the Socialist Workers Party (SWP): the use of the Internet in disagreements about confidential party issues.
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] He complained about "the dark side of the Internet" in which individuals have "used blogs and social media to launch a campaign within the SWP".
[src:chris-bambery/alex-callinicos] In order to disentangle a conference organised by the *Historical Materialism* journal in Delhi during 2013 from the SWP crisis, his invitation to the conference was withdrawn in March 2013.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] The **Anti-Nazi League** (**ANL**) was an organisation set up in 1977 on the initiative of the Socialist Workers Party (SWP) with sponsorship from some trade unions and the endorsement of a list of prominent people to oppose the rise of far-right groups in the United Kingdom.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] It was relaunched in 1992, but merged into Unite Against Fascism in 2003.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] It was initially led by a triumvirate of SWP member Paul Holborow, Labour Party member Peter Hain, and senior AUEW official Ernie Roberts.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] In its first period, 1977–1982, the Anti-Nazi League was launched directly by the SWP; it was effectively its front organisation.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Many trade unions sponsored it, as did the Indian Workers' Association (then a large organisation), and many members of the Labour Party, including MPs such as Neil Kinnock and future MPs such as trade unionist Ernie Roberts and anti-apartheid campaigner Peter Hain.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] According to socialist historian Dave Renton, the ANL was "an orthodox united front" based on a "strategy of working class unity", as advocated by Leon Trotsky.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Critics of the ANL, such as Anti-Fascist Action argue that the ANL's co-operation with "bourgeois" groups who work closely with the state, such as *Searchlight* magazine and the Labour Party, rule out this description, making it a classic popular front.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Most of the ANL's leafleting and other campaigns in the 1970s were in opposition to far right groups which it claimed were not just racist but fascist, such as the National Front, an organisation led by John Tyndall who had a long history of involvement with openly fascist and Nazi groups.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] The ANL also campaigned against the British Movement which was a more openly Hitlerite grouping.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] The ANL was linked to Rock Against Racism in the 1970s, which ran two giant carnivals in 1978 involving bands such as The Clash, Stiff Little Fingers, Steel Pulse, Misty in Roots, X-Ray Spex and Tom Robinson, attended by 80,000 and then 100,000 supporters.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Although the SWP leadership eventually turned against this "dual track" approach to anti-fascism – expelling many leading "squadists" in a purge in late 1981 – it is said to have proved an effective strategy during the ANL's early years from 1977 to 1979.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] In April 1979, an ANL member, Blair Peach, was killed following a demonstration at Southall against a National Front election meeting.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Police had sealed off the area around Southall Town Hall, and demonstrators trying to make their way there were blocked.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] In the ensuing confrontation, more than 40 people (including 21 police) were injured, and 300 were arrested.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Bricks were allegedly hurled at police, who described the rioting as the most violent they had handled in London.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] During an incident in a side street 100 yards from the town hall, he was seriously injured and collapsed after being struck on the head, allegedly by an unauthorised weapon used by a member of the police Special Patrol Group.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] An inquest jury later returned a verdict of misadventure, and no police officer was ever charged or prosecuted, although an internal police inquiry at the time and not released officially for 30 years, thought he had been killed by an unidentifiable police officer.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] A primary school in Southall bears his name.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] In 1981, with the eclipse of the National Front and collapse of the British Movement, the initial incarnation of the ANL was wound up.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Some elements within the ANL opposed the winding up of the organisation, including some members of the SWP.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] After being expelled from the Socialist Workers Party some of these elements formed Red Action and with others organised Anti-Fascist Action.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] In the early 1990s, the far right, and in particular the British National Party (BNP) was resurgent both electorally and in terms of racial attacks (from 4,383 in 1988 to 7,780 three years later).
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] When the National Front and the British National Party had been led by John Tyndall, his record of involvement in openly neo-Nazi groups made it far easier to assert that the National Front and BNP were fascist or neo-Nazi in nature.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Similarly, Tyndall's convictions for violence and incitement to racial hatred provide ample grounds for the ANL to claim both organisations were racist.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] After 1992, the ANL and other anti-fascists argued that the BNP remained a Nazi party irrespective of the fact that under the leadership of Nick Griffin it adopted what the ANL described as the 'Dual Strategy' of cultivating respectability in the media while retaining a cadre of committed fascists.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] This position was countered by BNP members who said that their party is increasingly democratic in its nature.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] An investigation by *The Guardian* newspaper on 22 December 2006 reported that the BNP remained a fascist party.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] ANL's relaunch was criticised by other anti-racists.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] The recently launched broad-based Anti-Racist Alliance said: "The ANL is an exercise in nostalgia.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] Anti-fascist magazine *Searchlight* criticised the "politics of deceit being practised by the SWP", accusing the ANL of deliberately exaggerating the danger posed by the BNP.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] However, Doreen Lawrence came to realise that the ANL was a "front for the Socialist Workers Party".
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] In 2001, an event it planned in Burnley was banned by the Home Secretary.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] ANL worked with Love Music Hate Racism (based on the earlier Rock Against Racism), from 2002 onwards.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] In 2004, the ANL affiliated with the National Assembly Against Racism to relaunch as Unite Against Fascism.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] The ANL National Organiser at the time of the creation of Unite Against Fascism was Weyman Bennett, a member of the Central Committee of the Socialist Workers Party as was Julie Waterson, its previous National Organiser.
[src:chris-bambery/anti-nazi-league] This "welcome and timely" call to action was supported in a *Guardian* letter signed by the league's founders, which included former Labour minister Peter Hain, political activist Paul Holborow and leading musicians from Rock Against Racism.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] Born in Paisley, near Glasgow, and raised in Dunoon, Morton was educated at the University of Edinburgh and taught in the late 1970s at the University of East Anglia (under Malcolm Bradbury) and at the University of Tromsø in Norway.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] From 1992 to 1997, Morton was the main presenter of *Impressions* for BBC Radio 3, a fortnightly jazz and improvised music programme.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] For more than a decade Morton was a familiar voice on music programmes and features on other arts related subjects on the London-based BBC networks.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] For some years, he was one of the presenters and a producer of *The Usual Suspects*, Later, he hosted *The Brian Morton Show* on BBC Radio Scotland, until 2003 after criticising the BBC's arts coverage.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] He is co-author, with Richard Cook, of *The Penguin Guide to Jazz Recordings* (formerly *...on CD)*, whose ninth edition (undertaken single-handed following Cook's premature death in 2007) was published at the end of October 2008.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] He is also the author of *The Blackwell Guide to Recorded Contemporary Music* (1996), which covers modern classical music.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] Morton was a frequent contributor to *Jazz Review* magazine, and was briefly editor in 2008; the magazine was absorbed by *Jazz Journal* in 2009, for which Morton has written.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] A biography, *Miles Davis*, was issued by Haus Publishing in 2005.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] He is a long-standing contributor to *The Wire* and to the Catholic weekly *The Tablet*.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] Morton converted to Catholicism in 1984.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] Morton's non-jazz books include translations from the Norwegian of Jonas Lie, *Prince: Thief in the Temple* (Canongate Books) and *Shostakovich* (Haus).
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] A short biography of the writer Edgar Allan Poe appeared in November 2009.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] Morton has been a 'Comment' columnist in the Scottish edition of *The Observer* newspaper and, like his American namesake, is an occasional contributor to *The Nation* magazine.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] In 2011, Morton relocated to Kintyre, moving with his family into a small former monastery.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] He now writes and farms with his wife, landscape photographer Sarah Morton.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] Morton also has two older daughters from a previous relationship.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] He is writing a biographical study of St Columba.
[src:chris-bambery/brian-morton-scottish-writer] He holds an honorary D.Litt. from the University of St Andrews, awarded on St Andrews Day, 2000, for services to Scottish broadcasting and cultural life.
[src:chris-bambery/charlie-kimber] Kimber has been politically active since the 1970s and went on his first protest march in 1975.
[src:chris-bambery/charlie-kimber] He is the editor of *Socialist Worker* newspaper and has also written for *International Socialism*, the SWP's journal of socialist theory.
[src:chris-bambery/charlie-kimber] He is a director of Sherborne Publications Limited, the company that publishes the *Socialist Worker*, having taken that position following the resignation of Martin Smith as a director on 24 May 2013.
[src:chris-bambery/charlie-kimber] Kimber has published a number of political works, mostly published by the Socialist Workers Party.
[src:chris-bambery/charlie-kimber] The cause of inflation, he asserted, was employers trying to maintain their profits in times of falling sales.
[src:chris-bambery/charlie-kimber] Other topics covered in the publication include the gap between rich and poor and the need for socialist organisation in order to achieve an economy planned in everyone's interests.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Prior to the 2017 UK General Election he was the Parliamentary Assistant to Scottish National Party MP George Kerevan.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] A leading member of the International Socialist Group, he was a member of the Central Committee of the Socialist Workers Party until 2011 when he resigned from the party.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] He is the author of the 2014 book *A People's History of Scotland* and was the editor of the UK's *Socialist Worker* newspaper.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] He was educated at the fee-paying Daniel Stewart's College and the University of Edinburgh, where he was Vice President of the Students' Representative Council.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Bambery began his political career as a member of the International Marxist Group (IMG) in 1972.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Bambery was appointed to the new "breakaway-breakaway" party's steering committee, but following its collapse soon afterwards he resumed his role as an IMG activist, becoming the group's full-time organiser in Glasgow in 1978.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Bambery left the IMG in May 1979, joining the Socialist Workers Party (SWP) seven months later.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] In 1981, he became the SWP's Glasgow organiser.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Two years later, he moved to London as an organiser for the SWP, was elected a member of its Central Committee in 1987 and became its National Organiser shortly afterwards, a position which he held until 2004, when he replaced Chris Harman as editor of *Socialist Worker*.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] In 2001, he led the International Socialist Tendency at the Genoa Group of Eight Summit protest in Italy with fellow SWP member Alex Callinicos.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] After considerable political tension within the SWP regarding the party's response to the economic crisis, Bambery made public his resignation letter to SWP National Organiser Charlie Kimber on 11 April 2011.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Following his resignation from the SWP, Bambery was a founding member of the International Socialist Group, an organisation set up by the 39 former SWP members to formulate a united front approach to the recession and to develop a Left argument for Scottish independence in the 2014 referendum.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] During the referendum campaign, Bambery supported the Radical Independence Campaign, and was subsequently a supporter of RISE, the Scottish radical left coalition.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] In 2014, Bambery's *A People's History of Scotland* and his *The Second World War: A Marxist History* were published.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Thompson's *The Making of the English Working Class*" Brian Morton in *The Herald* described its "relentless populism" as "tiresome", but concluded that it was "pamphleteering of an attractively old-fashioned sort, but on an ambitious scale...
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Some criticism came from those who maintain a loyalty to the former USSR and did not like the depiction of it as fighting the war with Germany for its own, imperialist interests.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] In March 2018 *Catalonia Reborn*, co-authored by Chris and George Kerevan, was published by Luath Press, and in August 2018 Verso published a new, updated edition of A People's History of Scotland.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] "The book is a sustained indictment of the Spanish government’s dealings with Catalonia, made all the more devastating by the detailed factual nature of the work.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] 'Perhaps it is true that there is no good news in history: the excellent work of Chris Bambery, expanding on an acclaimed article on the same theme, supports that point as it applies to the comparatively recent past in Scotland.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] Parallels with contemporary anti-immigration racism are unavoidable.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-bambery] A minister at the 1922 General Assembly of the Church of Scotland proclaimed: “Roman Catholics of Irish origin… were not only alien to Scots in religion; they were also alien in race.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] Harman was born into a working-class family and attended Leeds University (where he joined the Socialist Review Group in 1961) and the London School of Economics (LSE) where he began (but did not complete) a doctorate under the supervision of Ralph Miliband.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] He was instrumental in publishing the magazine of the LSE Socialist Society, *The Agitator*, and was a leading member of the International Socialists (as the SRG had become) by 1968.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] He was involved in the Vietnam Solidarity Campaign and outraged many leftists when, at a meeting in the Conway Hall, he denounced Ho Chi Minh for murdering the leader of the Vietnamese Trotskyist movement, Tạ Thu Thâu, in 1945 after crushing the workers' rising of that year in Saigon.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] His main role in the IS (from 1977 the Socialist Workers Party, or SWP) was as a theorist and he produced numerous books and articles on a wide variety of topics.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] Almost all his writing appeared in the publications of the IS and SWP or has been published by related publishing houses, such as Bookmarks.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] He was first editor of *Socialist Worker* in 1976-77 and returned to the role after a break in 1982, remaining in the post until 2004, when he started editing the SWP's theoretical quarterly *International Socialism Journal*.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] Harman's work on the May 1968 events in France and other student and workers' uprisings of the late 1960s, *The Fire Last Time*, was recommended by rock band Rage Against the Machine in the album liner notes for *Evil Empire*.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] Harman died on 7 November 2009, following a cardiac arrest while lecturing at the Socialist Days conference of the Center for Socialist Studies (CSS) in Cairo, Egypt.
[src:chris-bambery/chris-harman] He is buried in Highgate Cemetery, London, a few yards from Karl Marx's tomb and adjacent to his comrade Paul Foot.
